Okay, during the day I hung up the new nest box. Here's what it looks like in the garden.
But let's take a step back. "What's inside?" seems to be a question no one has asked.
The top is an ESP32 camera board with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED I took off a Raspberry Pi camera.
The plastic box has an odd shape because the side panel of the nest box can rotate. It was like this when I bought it, and it couldn't be modified, so I had to design around this situation.
Since there's no power source in the garden, the whole setup is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 lithium-ion battery.
I didn't take pictures of the battery or charger, but here's a picture of the solar panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the nest box contains the battery.
After being charged, it can run for about 4 hours.
I call this a "special feature." This way, the birds can also have some private space.
At first, I wasn't sure if the network in the garden was good enough to support this setup. The old access points I replaced last autumn definitely wouldn't work.
But the coverage of the new access point is completely fine.
Well, now I was even planning to install a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof aimed downwards at the garden.
If I were to set up more nest boxes with cameras in the future, I might still do it this way. Especially in places farther away from the house, I might need it.
